The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Friday, December 12, 2003 				 Inquiry into patient death 
 A STAFF REPORTER																								The government has set up a three-member committee to inquire into the death of a patient at Nilratan Sircar (NRS) Medical College and Hospital on Wednesday night. 																								Raju Mahato, the victim, was injured in a road mishap and succumbed to his injuries in hospital. Relatives complained that Raju had died due to negligence on the part of the doctors on duty.																								Sources in the health department said that stung by yet another allegation of a patients death because of hospital neglect, the government asked the inquiry committee, comprising doctors B.P. Chakraborty of the surgery wing, A.B. Bera of medicine and Sri Ray of plastic surgery, to start the probe right away. The report has been sought at the earliest.																								Entally police station officials said Raju was hit by a private bus on the Sealdah flyover around 9 pm on Wednesday. He was on his way to Beleghata on a scooter. An unidentified person brought him to NRS and got him admitted there. Raju died in the hospital around 11.30 pm.																								His relatives later lodged a complaint with the police and the hospital authorities, alleging that Raju had died due to gross negligence on the part of the doctors. 																								Their complaint said Raju had been fully conscious till 11 pm and had himself furnished his name and address to the doctors attending to him.																								The relatives said the doctors had not given Raju any medication at all. It was only when his condition started deteriorating that a junior doctor was called in to attend to him and put him on oxygen. Rajus relatives also alleged that the doctors had misbehaved with them when questioned about the reasons behind his death.																								The government is seriously concerned with yesterdays incident. The inquiry team has been asked to cross-examine each and every one on duty last night, said an official in the health department.
